Variations in disease presence in association with country and age were no longer significant in multivariable analysis. However, reduced odds of disease remained significantly associated with a history of vaccination for CPIV, CAV-2 or CDV with an independent effect of reduced odds of disease in shelter dogs and dogs from other sources compared with client-owned dogs (Table 2
). Further examination of the vaccination effect indicated that the proportion of dogs with a history of vaccination against CPIV, CAV-2 and CDV reduced significantly as the severity of disease increased (Fig. 1
).
